  "notes": "Middle Persian / Pahlavi (~224вЂ“900 CE). Language of the Sasanian Empire (224вЂ“651 CE) and Zoroastrian religious texts. KEY INNOVATIONS vs. Old Persian: (1) Intervocalic consonant LENITION: pв†’w/b, tв†’d (Оёв†’d), kв†’gв†’Оі; (2) Diphthong MONOPHTHONGISATION: *ai в†’ Д“ [eЛђ], *au в†’ ЕЌ [oЛђ]; (3) 6-quality vowel system: a, ДЃ, Д“, Д«, ЕЌ, Е«; (4) xw- cluster preserved as /xК·/ (later в†’ x in New Persian). Script: Pahlavi (Aramaeographic; Aramaic logograms 'huzvarishn'). Arabic conquest (651 CE): Arabic becomes administrative language; Arabic loanwords begin entering. ISO 639-2: pal (Pahlavi). References: Mackenzie (1971), Brunner (1977).",
